    understandingLevels: {
        novice: {
            characteristics: [
                "Can state definitions of producer, consumer, decomposer, and food chain",
                "Knows that energy decreases along a food chain but cannot explain why or quantify the loss",
                "Confuses energy flow (unidirectional) with nutrient cycling (cyclical)",
                "Cannot distinguish nitrification from nitrogen fixation",
                "Treats carrying capacity as a fixed ceiling that never changes",
                "Does not yet connect biodiversity to ecosystem stability"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Draw energy flow as a one-way arrow from sun → producer → consumer → heat (dissipated out of the system). Draw nutrient cycling as a closed loop with arrows going in both directions between biotic and abiotic compartments. Use two completely separate diagrams — never mix them on the same page until both are automatic separately.",
                "Practise the 10% rule with simple multiplication: given any NPP value, calculate energy at levels 2, 3, 4 by multiplying by 0.1 each time. Do five examples with different NPP values before attempting to explain the underlying mechanism.",
                "For the nitrogen cycle: before any memorisation, write out what each stage does in one plain-English sentence. Fixation = 'bacteria turn N₂ gas into a form plants can use.' Nitrification = 'bacteria turn ammonia into nitrate.' Denitrification = 'bacteria turn nitrate back into N₂ gas.' Read these aloud three times before attempting to draw the cycle.",
                "For carrying capacity: draw three separate K scenarios — K in good years, K in drought years, K after habitat destruction. Annotate each one to show K changing. This prevents the static-ceiling misconception.",
                "For biodiversity and stability: use a simple analogy — a redundant electrical circuit (multiple pathways between two points) keeps working if one wire breaks; a circuit with a single wire fails immediately. Map this to functional redundancy in ecosystems."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "Energy is recycled like nutrients → two-diagram approach (above)",
                "10% rule is exact → practise calculating and annotate 'approximately' each time",
                "Nitrification vs fixation confusion → plain-English sentence approach (above)"
            ]
        },

        developing: {
            characteristics: [
                "Can apply the 10% rule to calculate energy at each trophic level given NPP",
                "Can name all nitrogen cycle stages but sometimes misorders nitrification and ammonification",
                "Understands that density-dependent factors regulate populations but gives vague examples",
                "Can draw a basic food web but cannot explain trophic cascades or the consequences of removing a species",
                "Knows the definition of resilience but cannot explain how biodiversity confers it mechanistically"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "For nitrogen cycle ordering: write the cycle as a narrative of a nitrogen atom's journey — 'I start as N₂ in the air. A Rhizobium bacterium in a legume root converts me to NH₄⁺ (fixation). I'm incorporated into plant protein. The plant dies. A decomposer breaks me down to NH₄⁺ again (ammonification). Nitrosomonas converts me to NO₂⁻, then Nitrobacter to NO₃⁻ (nitrification). A plant root absorbs me. I'm eaten by an animal. The animal excretes me as urea. I'm ammonified again. Eventually, in a waterlogged soil, Pseudomonas converts me to N₂ and I return to the atmosphere (denitrification).' Read and re-write this narrative from memory.",
                "For trophic cascades: use the Yellowstone wolf example as a template. Practice tracing three levels up and three levels down from any species removal: what happens to prey, to vegetation, to competitors, to decomposers. Apply the template to two other ecosystems before the exam.",
                "For resilience and functional redundancy: draw an ecosystem with five species performing the same function (e.g. five different nitrogen-fixing bacteria species). Remove species one by one and ask whether the function is maintained. At what point does it fail? This operationalises functional redundancy.",
                "For density-dependent factors: require yourself to give a mechanism with every example. Not just 'disease increases' but 'as population density increases, individuals are in closer contact, disease transmission rates increase because pathogen contact rate is proportional to the square of density in a well-mixed population.'"
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "Nitrification and ammonification ordering → atom narrative approach (above)",
                "Trophic cascade mechanism → template application (above)",
                "Resilience without mechanism → functional redundancy diagram (above)"
            ]
        },

        proficient: {
            characteristics: [
                "Calculates NPP, energy at each trophic level, and ecological efficiency accurately",
                "Draws fully labelled carbon and nitrogen cycles with all major fluxes annotated",
                "Correctly applies logistic growth equation and interprets the growth rate at different N values",
                "Can explain trophic cascades with specific examples and trace effects across multiple levels",
                "Can distinguish resilience from resistance and explain the biodiversity mechanism for each",
                "Correctly identifies and explains eutrophication mechanism from input to hypoxia"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Calculate and compare ecological efficiencies across five real ecosystems (research published values). Explain why efficiency varies between ecosystem types and what this means for the food chain length each can support.",
                "Trace a phosphorus atom through the entire phosphorus cycle in a forest-stream-lake system, annotating residence times in each compartment. Note where phosphorus accumulates (sediment, biomass) and where it moves quickly (soil water). This reveals why phosphorus limitation is so common.",
                "Practice the Hill equation analogy for population growth: in logistic growth, as N approaches K, growth slows the way enzyme velocity slows as substrate concentration approaches saturation — draw the parallel explicitly. This connects population ecology to biochemistry and deepens both.",
                "Apply the intermediate disturbance hypothesis to three different ecosystems (coral reef, grassland, temperate forest) and predict how changing disturbance frequency would shift species diversity in each. Test whether IDH predictions are consistent across very different ecosystem types."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "10% rule as exact → calculate actual efficiencies from real data and compare to the 10% approximation",
                "Pyramids of biomass always upright → research a specific aquatic example and explain why phytoplankton biomass < zooplankton biomass despite phytoplankton being the base"
            ]
        },

        expert: {
            characteristics: [
                "Derives NPP and energy transfer equations from first principles and applies them to novel ecosystems",
                "Designs field studies to measure GPP, NPP, and ecological efficiency with appropriate controls",
                "Interprets published population time-series data, fits logistic growth models, and identifies deviations from model predictions",
                "Analyses nutrient budgets for whole ecosystems using published flux data",
                "Connects ecosystem-level processes to global biogeochemical cycles and climate feedbacks"
            ],
            immediateNextSteps: [
                "Investigate the IPCC carbon budget: obtain published values for terrestrial GPP, ocean carbon uptake, and fossil fuel emissions. Calculate the net annual carbon flux and connect it to the atmospheric CO₂ concentration change. This operationalises the carbon cycle at planetary scale.",
                "Critically evaluate the intermediate disturbance hypothesis using published meta-analyses. Identify the conditions under which IDH holds and where it breaks down. Evaluate the evidence for unimodal vs monotonic diversity-disturbance relationships in different ecosystem types.",
                "Apply metabolic scaling theory (Kleiber's law) to predict how ecosystem-level metabolic rates change with organism body size distribution. Explore how this affects energy transfer efficiency between trophic levels in ecosystems dominated by large vs small organisms.",
                "Model a two-species Lotka-Volterra predator-prey system. Derive the equations, identify equilibrium conditions, and analyse the stability of the equilibrium using the Jacobian matrix. Connect the oscillation period to the Yellowstone time-series data from the contextual scenario."
            ],
            misconceptionsToAddress: [
                "GPP as a fixed property of an ecosystem → explore how GPP varies seasonally, with drought, and with CO₂ fertilisation using flux tower data",
                "Logistic growth as the universal model → investigate chaotic dynamics at high r/K ratios and compare to real population time-series"
            ]
        }
    }
